topic.title: TLP Generator and Checker Command

body.p: MRPC Command ID: 0xETLP Checker is de featured (prep 479820)

TLP Generator (GEN) is a diagnostic feature that allows the user to transfer and receive sustained and configurable TLP traffic. These diagnostic features are used for internal or external data path signal integrity and bandwidth testing. A few of the key features of the TLP Generator are:
• User defined TLP headers
• Configurable payload size and data
• TLP count and transferring gap configuration

section.title: Internal information
section.p: From the Hardware view point, the TLP GEN and CHK is a sub-block of the PPU. To correctly function, the GEN and CHK are required to be separately connected to a PPU channel. The exception to this is if the diagnostic test target is an internal data path, then the GEN and CHK can be connected to the same PPU channel. For external data path testing GEN and CHK can be in different devices.

In Firmware design, since different PPU channels already have their defined applications, the only free channel available is channel#6. The user is required to connect GEN and CHK to channel#6 and use the default 0x19(8x2) bifurcation settings to avoid corrupting the normal traffic through the PPU. If users want to use other bifurcation mode PPU channels for testing purposes, then the x16, x8, x4, x2 PPU channels are also supported.

There are two modes supported by the TLP Generator:
PPU Loopback Mode
PPU SC Port Mode

Loopback Mode is a debug mode where outbound data at the switch core interface is used to internally drive the switch core inbound interface. Loopback mode also acts on the whole PPU, not only the PPU channels for GEN and CHK. Outbound TLP of any PPU channel would be looped-back to the current PPU channels inbound interface, before going to the switch core to arbitrate. This mode is not recommended when the device is active in a PCIe topology.

In PPU SC Port Mode, when the TLP reaches the SC interface it is routed to an egress port. The destination port is determined by the user by configuring the SC metadata. The RST in PPU-ISP is bypassed and the RST configuration in PPU-ISP is not covered by the TLP GEN and CHK feature.

The TLP Checker also features a performance timer. The CHK performance counter can be configured for how many TLPs the Checker is expected to receive. A CHK performance timer is started when the first good TLP is received and stops after receiving the configured number of good TLPs. The timer can be read to calculate the performance.

As multiple MRPC hosts and FW CLIs could access the TLP GEN CHK module at the same time. There is an access permission mechanism to prevent multiple sources from accessing the module. When the TLP GEN CHK module is free, MRPC hosts or FW CLI can freely access the module. However, once access permission is granted the other hosts or FW CLI cannot access the module until the host or FW CLI release the access permission.

For MRPC initiators, when the Generator completes sending its TLPs and the Checker completes receiving TLPs or the Checker receives an error TLP. There will be an asynchronous notification to notify the host, the host will need to dump the status of TLP GEN CHK for more detailed information.

body.p:
There are two modes supported by the TLP Generator:
Loopback Mode
Port Mode

Loopback Mode is a debug mode where outbound data at the switch core interface is used to internally drive the switch core inbound interface. This mode cannot be used in an active in a PCIe topology. If the port is bifurcated to x16, x8, or x4, the switch will not be able to send/receive TLPs or respond to MRPC commands. A switch reset is required to recover.
In Port Mode, when the TLP reaches the switch core interface it is routed to an egress port. The destination port is determined by the user by configuring the port in the MRPC.
As multiple MRPC hosts and FW CLIs could access the TLP GEN module at the same time. There is an access permission mechanism to prevent multiple sources from accessing the module.
For MRPC initiators, when the Generator completes sending its TLPs there will be an asynchronous notification to notify the host.

body.p: This field indicates the sub-command ID to perform operation on TLP GEN. Refer "MRPC TLP Generator Checker Sub-Commands" table for different sub-command.
This field indicates which PPU channel is to be connected to Generator.
This field is initial data seed value used to generate TLP data for GEN or check TLP data for CHK.
This field indicates the gap between generated TLPs in 500 MHz clock cycles. 0x0 means send TLP back to back. 0x1 indicates the gap is 2 ns.

This field contains the number of TLPs to generate for GEN or the number of TLPs expected to be checked for CHK. A value of zero in this field indicates that TLPs would be generated as long as GEN was started and CHK should sustain to receive and check TLPs.
If the TLP Type is different between GEN and CHK, this TLP Count field must not be set to zero.PREP#437503

This field indicates the TLP type of header user defined. “1” means Posted TLP. “2” means Non-posted TLP. “4” means Completion. The TLP Type value must be either 1, 2, or 4, all other values are reserved and must not be used.(PREP#437513)
This field indicates the header size. “0” means 3DWs header and “1” means 4DWs header.
This field indicates the payload size in DW of generated and expected to check TLPs.

This field specifies the manner in which polarity inversion is applied to generated TLP DWs. 0 means generated TLP DW values are never inverted. 2 means every other 320-bit generated TLP value is inverted. 3 means every other 160-bit generated TLP value is inverted. This field acts on both GEN and CHK.

This field specifies the manner in which data payload values are generated. 0 means all DW data in TLP payload is constant value defined in <TLP SEED DATA> field. 1 means payload data of every TLP would increase by 1 per DW. Payload of the next TLP would continue to increase by 1 rather than use the initial value defined in <TLP SEED DATA> field. 2 means DW data of each TLP payload is constant value but would increase by 1 for each TLP.
This field indicates the input maximum 4DWs TLP headers. If TLP type is of 3DWs header, then just have to input 3DWs. This field should be identify for GEN and CHK.
This field indicates the source port to fill into the SC metadata. Normally user could neglect this field and fill it with 0.
This field indicates the source partition to fill into the SC metadata. Normally user could neglect this field and fill it with 0.
This field indicates the destination port that generated TLP is expectedly to route.
